<tr><td id=bigrow valign=top>Faction Theories:<hr size=1><td></tr>
<tr><td>
Much has been theorized about how factions work in Norrath.  Some has been proven, yet much of it reamins a grey area which little is known about. This forum provides an opportunity to try and compare evidence on various issues with faction.<p>
Faction is, as most of us know, a measure of how a segment of the population of Norrath think of you.  It affects your ability to do quests.  It affects your ability to shop, buy and sell.  It affects which areas of the world your character treats as safe versus dangerous.<p>
It has been stated by Verant that the way a certain faction will treat you depends on 4 base factors:
<ul>
<li>Your race
<li>Your class
<li>Your religion (choice of deity)
<li>Your actions or deeds
</ul>
The first three of these factors (with few exceptions) are fixed.  Without the use of a race modifying Illusion, you're stuck as you were born.  Your class is always fixed, and as has been stated numerous times, Religion is calculated at character creation.  This leaves deeds (either questing or killing things) for 90% of the population to adjust their factions.<p>

Many people have asked for the ability to change ones religion, Verant has continually denied this request, based I beleive on the way religion faction works.  Religion faction is treated as modifiers at character creation, where factions are "seeded" in terms of how they think of you.  Though not impossible to change, it certainly would be tricky<p>

It was pointed out to me a while back that each NPC really has only one faction (this bestiary wasn't designed that way, oops).  The first faction message you see is the faction which that person belongs to.  Any further faction messages are meerly the alignements that primary faction has.  Examples of this are the Solusek Mining Co, which is aligned with many factions in Ak'Anon.  When you hunt in Solusek's Eye killing the gnomes, you lower all of Ak'Anon, yes the gnomes there only respond to Solusek Mining Co faction which can be raised next door via the Kobolds.<p>

For a given faction, the alignment remains static (unless adjusted by verant) and is always the same.<p>

One thing which has been the subject of many a debate is faction limits.  The degree to which you can modify the way a faction thinks of you via your deeds.  Some believe that you can only reach certain hard caps in the faction as a whole, yet others believe that certain deeds (ie Quest XX) only raise your faction so much with a given group, and that once you've maxed it therem you need to move on.<p>

I would love to see any evidence people have in this regard.<p>

--Illia


