<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9714723808886></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9714723808886><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/facstrat.html?forum=3&mid=9714723808886 style='color: darkblue;'>Assorted thoughts</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=651><span id=>Verdandi</span></a><br><span id=notbold>10 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Oct 13th 5:26 PM</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>First of all, on the "line in the sand," a point of no return from which you can never go back:  I remember reading a post by Abashi in which he stated that it is entirely possible to become so despised that no number of good deeds can ever earn back good graces.  The analogy that he says they kept in mind is if, in real life, you run around killing old ladies (or something like that) but then contribute to a charity in order to earn back faction with TheGeneralPublic.  If your crimes are horrific enough, there is nothing you can do be forgiven.  Now that said, we all know that you can do some pretty horrific things without faction budging at all.  I, a barbarian shaman who is amiable with my guards, once accidentally killed one (thought I had the skeleton targeted but actually had poor Arnis McLish and one DD popped him off).  I was absolutely horrified, but my guards remained amiable.  So chances are if you're starting with decent faction, an accident or two won't condemn you completely.  But it seems to imply that, in response to Illia's question, there is a separately calculated cap on how much negative faction you can accumulate before they just hate you permanently.<br><br>I also distinctly recall Abashi once saying that *any* class/race/diety combination can do *any* quest.  This means that with sufficient work, any faction can be raised (probably to warmly, since most factions have a quest that requires it) by anyone at all.  The catch appears to be that some factions simply cannot be raised without lowering those of others.  Sure, a wood elf can stroll through the walkways of Neriak, but woe to ye if ye try to reenter Kelethin afterwards.  I've searched high and low for things to make me more than amiable to the Halas guards and the only things I've found involve killing dark elves (which they don't much appreciate) or are quests within Halas that upset the rogues.  It would be really sweet to be able to be non-kos with every faction there is, or at least all of the player races, but it doesn't look very possible.  <br><br>Also, it is common knowledge that you will only receive positive faction hits (not sure about negative ones) for a certain quest or killing a certain thing for so long.  Eventually you max out the positive hits you can get for that critter or quest.  The problem is that once this happens you stop getting not just that faction hit, but all of them that were associated with that critter or quest, even if you should still be able to get more.  That doesn't quite make sense that you would be able to get more, because if the cap is only on positive faction relating to that one quest or critter, then you would be getting the hits for all of them, so they should all max at the same time...unless they have different caps.  Seems awfully complicated.  But Abashi seemed concerned by that report and said he would investigate...sure sounded like you should be able to max one faction on a quest or critter and still receive the other hits after that.  This would imply that there might be caps not only on how much Qeynos Guards faction you can get off of killing gnolls or off of turning in bandit sashes, but also caps independently calculated on how much positive faction you can get overall with the same Guards of Qeynos.  <br><br>Lemme know if parts of this didn't make sense and I'll try to clarify :)<br><br>-Verdandi Snowblood of Karana<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

</ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9714636618913></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9714636618913><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/facstrat.html?forum=3&mid=9714636618913 style='color: darkblue;'>To the best of my knowledge...</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=768><span id=>Teramenor</span></a><br><span id=notbold>9 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Oct 13th 3:01 PM</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Your standing with a faction is the combined value of those four numbers.  Let's take a random faction, like MayongMistmoore.  You start at a neutral faction of, say, 0.  (Positive scores mean they like you, negative means they hate you.)  Because you're a dwarf, you have a -50 race modifier.  Because you're a cleric, you have a -25 class modifier.  (I'm making up these numbers.)  Because you worship Brell Serilis, you get another -50.  So your BASE standing with Mistmoore is -120.  Now you can do actions, kill things that oppose Mistmoore to raise faction.  Let's say that your "Actions" component has a cap of +100.  So you kill hundreds of whatever, and now your actions component is at +100.  So given your race, class, and god, the HIGHEST faction you can EVER have with Mistmoore is -20.<br><br>This is how I *THINK* the system works, but it's hard to prove :)  To recap, the first three faction types are a fixed value (unless you disguise your race with illusions or spells, but that's obviously temporary).  The last faction value has a maximum range from -N to +N, and you simply add up all four values to get your final faction.  This is why you may never be higher than, say, dubious with a certain faction, no matter how many millions of orcs you kill.  Or something.<br><br>Does this sound like it makes any sense? :)<br><br>- Teramenor Earthgate<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

